        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-05T14:10:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The GrSurfaceContext::rescale() function is still used for the async readback feature in chromium, right? What are the implications of switching to approx fit textures here then? Do they remain in skia\u0027s resource definitions so it\u0027s transparent to them?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 621,
        "startChar": 56,
        "endLine": 621,
        "endChar": 77
      },
      "revId": "a0011cc8cf54f3c130a056fe8ecfbea83b18cc4f",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "4f2f8673_b5d9b8a8",
        "filename": "src/gpu/GrSurfaceContext.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 17
      },
      "lineNbr": 621,
      "author": {
        "id": 5085
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-06T16:01:10Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It should be transparent to them. They never see these textures. If you were only every reading back one sized buffer repeatedly you might use a little more memory, but you might save memory if you\u0027re resizing a window that\u0027s being read back through better texture reuse. Because of interpolation/floating point you can get slightly different pixel values in your read back (or perhaps significantly different in kLow/nearest mode on edge cases).\n\nI\u0027ll run the Chrome tests again just to double check that no image tests get tripped up.",
      "parentUuid": "d04b1aff_b38951cf",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 621,
        "startChar": 56,
        "endLine": 621,
        "endChar": 77
      },
